The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, April 4: The power situation improved today with the National Thermal Power Corporation restarting a 200-mw unit at Farakka. 

 One 500-mw unit and another 200-mw one had to be shut down on Saturday because of water scarcity. State electricity board officials said the combined shortfall in CESC- and SEB-served areas this evening was 120 mw. Calcutta and its adjoining areas experi- enced brief spells of power cuts. In the districts, the shortfall was 80 mw, 270 less than yesterday. 

 Chinsurah: The manager of a brick-kiln at Bhadreswar in Hooghly where the labourers and their families were kept in bondage has been arrested. Adlal Tewary was held along with his assistant. On Monday, The Telegraph had reported the rescue of 98 men, women and children and how they were tortured in two kilns, 50 km from Calcutta. 

 Calcutta: Ghani Khan Chowdhurys condition is stable. The Congresss Malda MP was admitted to a private hospital on Monday and diagnosed with stones in the gall bladder and kidneys. Jyoti Basu called up former state Congress president Somen Mitra on Tuesday to enquire about Ghani Khans health . 

 Calcutta: City police sleuths have arrested one Badal Das from South 24-Parganas for alle- gedly duping a man of Rs 34 lakh after promising to bag a contract for him. Das had allegedly collected the money from businessman Sankar Kundu in two instalments.

 Krishnagar: Four members of a family have died of a mystery disease in Nadias Habibpur, about 70 km from Calcutta, over the past week. About 20 other members of the joint family, who have fever and are vomiting, have been hospitalised.




